[00:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Okay, here are two security cameras. One is a full-fledged product, the other is a prototype involving a Raspberry Pi, a camera, and more tape than I\'d care to admit. If I had to pick between the two right now, I would take the terrible bundle of plastic and tape, hands down.'

[00:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; That\'s because the tech running on tape boy over here is a glimpse of the future. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; It\'s a new stack in the world of streaming video, Iro and Media over Quick, or Moq. To understand the bits that are new, we'

[00:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'first have to set a baseline by looking at the way things roughly work today. For the sake of argument, we will assume you can or have waited through the minefield of one-off products that do or don\'t work with each other and are all secretly just wrappers around FFmpeg'

[00:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '[music] and set up a wonderful generic streaming stack. At this point, it\'ll be driven by some tech that either is or looks a lot like WebRTC. &gt;&gt; [music]'

[00:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; The camera will start up, dial some server, and prepare to send video to the cloud. Standard industry practice is to encode multiple different streams of different quality directly on the device. This is happening whenever your device is sending video and is at least part of the reason why your laptop'

[01:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'battery gets so unbelievably sad when you join a video conferencing call. Iro and Moq looks a little different. The first thing to notice is that our little camera isn\'t generating any video at all right now because no one is'

[01:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'connected. This is the first really big win of Moq. It\'s pull-based. Streams are only created when someone asks for them, and this one incredibly simple difference is the biggest win for video efficiency generally.'

[01:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'It\'s less strain on batteries, it\'s less data over the network, which leaves more room for doomscrolling, [music] encoding other things, whatever you want to do. But to get to that, we have a problem. How do we connect to the camera to tell it to start sending video in the first'

[01:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'place? &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; And that\'s where Iro comes in. With connections that can literally dial from anywhere to anywhere. That means an app on your phone can reach out to a camera in your house, your car, your conference room, film set, football stadium,'

[01:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'wherever you want it to go. Iro would create an encrypted connection directly between the camera and your device. This means Iro gives us quick connections that work everywhere, and Mach gives us first-class streaming tools'

[02:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'purpose-built for Quick. If you look at how well all this lines up, you would think that we kind of like planned all this out in advance. But delightfully, this is just another win for open standards all coalescing around Quick. With Iro, you\'re always getting the'

[02:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'fastest connection possible. If you\'re in your house, the connection doesn\'t leave your house. If you\'re on the other side of the world, it\'ll find the shortest path possible through the internet. But the fact that the connection is'

[02:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'encrypted and direct is the reason I\'d pick this ridiculous hacky prototype even today. [music] Because I know exactly who can see this video stream, and it\'s only people that I choose. &gt;&gt; [music]'

[02:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; We think this really shines in the Internet of Things use case, because all this works on low-power devices, and that\'s frankly harder to do. But everything we\'ve shown here translates into wins for nearly all video streaming. We can seamlessly bridge this into browsers with WebRTC standards. We can use Mach relay servers to do all'

[03:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'kinds of classic video conferencing tricks like combining streams. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; We can fan this out for live streaming. We can even add tracks for time code and go into full broadcast mode if that\'s the kind of thing you need. For now, this is just kind of a taste of where we\'d like to go with video and Iro.'

[03:13] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Hopefully you find this interesting. Stay tuned for more. Join us on the Discord and come hang.'
